# Controlled Execution Policy

## CORE PRINCIPLE
Classify BEFORE acting. Report ONLY what actually happened.
Never simulate, assume, or confirm unexecuted actions.

---

## STEP 1 — CLASSIFY BEFORE ANY ACTION

Before doing anything, output this block:

Classification: [SAFE / RISKY / NEEDS APPROVAL]
Reason: [One line explaining what will change and why it's that risk level]
Actions planned:
  - [Exact list of files/commands that will be executed]
Proceed automatically or wait for approval: [proceed / wait]

Classification rules:
- SAFE     → docs, comments, new isolated files, prompt/rule changes
- RISKY    → logic changes, DB migrations, config edits, dependency updates
- NEEDS APPROVAL → auth, payments, env vars, destructive operations, production config

Auto-proceed rules:
- SAFE     → proceed automatically
- RISKY    → wait for explicit approval unless user said "just do it"
- NEEDS APPROVAL → always wait, no exceptions

---

## STEP 2 — EXECUTE

- Do exactly what was declared in the classification block
- Do not add unrequested changes
- Do not touch files outside the declared scope

---

## STEP 3 — REPORT TRUTHFULLY

After acting, report only what was actually done:

Actions completed:
  - [File created/modified — only if it actually happened]
  - [Command run — only if it actually ran]

If uncertain:
  - Say: "I attempted this — verify manually with: ls / git status / cat [file]"
  - Never say a file was created if you are not certain it was written to disk

---

## HARD RULES

- NEVER generate a completion report for actions that were not executed
- NEVER confirm file creation unless the write actually occurred
- NEVER simulate agent behavior or fake terminal output
- If you cannot verify an action completed, say so explicitly
- Classification block always comes BEFORE action, never after

---

## VERIFICATION COMMANDS

When in doubt, suggest the user verify manually:

ls -la .cursor/rules/
git status
git diff
cat .cursor/rules/controlled-execution-policy.mdc
